---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Configuration & Settings" showSidebar={true} activeSlug="settings">
  <div class="prose">
  <h1>Configuration &amp; Settings</h1>
  <p>BitBar allows you to configure your telemetry preferences through a graphical interface, which stores settings locally in the Windows registry.</p>

  <h2>Accessing Settings</h2>
  <p>To configure BitBar, simply <strong>right-click</strong> the network speed label on your Windows taskbar and choose <strong>"Settings"</strong>. This will open the settings dialog.</p>

  <h2>Available Preferences</h2>
  
  <h3>1. Network Adapter Binding</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Auto-Detect (Default):</strong> Automatically binds to the active network adapter routing your internet traffic. If you connect to a VPN or switch from Wi-Fi to Ethernet, BitBar will re-bind on the fly.</li>
    <li><strong>Manual Interface Pinning:</strong> Select a specific network card (e.g. <em>Intel(R) Wi-Fi 6E</em>, <em>Realtek Gaming Family Controller</em>, or your VPN tunnel adapter) to monitor only that interface.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>2. Display Units</h3>
  <p>Toggle between how the throughput speed is displayed on your taskbar and flyout:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>MB/s (Megabytes per second):</strong> Preferred for file downloads, storage sizes, and standard browser usage.</li>
    <li><strong>Mbps (Megabits per second):</strong> Preferred for network speedtests, ISP comparisons, and router bandwidth limits.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>3. Refresh Rate</h3>
  <p>Adjust the slider to control the polling frequency of the network interfaces (from <strong>100ms</strong> to <strong>5000ms</strong>).</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Lower Interval (e.g. 250ms):</strong> Gives highly precise real-time speed bursts but increases CPU interrupts slightly.</li>
    <li><strong>Higher Interval (e.g. 2000ms):</strong> Ideal for low-power laptops or maximum energy savings.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Registry Storage Details</h2>
  <p>All configurations are saved immediately without a background daemon in the Windows Registry. You can manually inspect or modify these settings using the Registry Editor (<code>regedit</code>) at:</p>

  <pre><code>Computer\HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Software\BitBar</code></pre>

  <p>The registry key holds the following DWORD/String attributes:</p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Value Name</th>
        <th>Type</th>
        <th>Description</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><code>AdapterName</code></td>
        <td>String (REG_SZ)</td>
        <td>The description name of the pinned adapter (or empty string for Auto-Detect).</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>DisplayUnits</code></td>
        <td>String (REG_SZ)</td>
        <td>Either <code>"MB/s"</code> or <code>"Mbps"</code>.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>RefreshInterval</code></td>
        <td>DWORD (REG_DWORD)</td>
        <td>Interval in milliseconds (e.g. <code>1000</code>).</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  </div>
</Layout>
